So this implementation looks plausible.
There is the general question though still of if conserver might be a preferred solution. Even if it has a BSD with advertising licence, and consequently is in debian non-free,
is this a particular issue for openstack? It's available in ubuntu and fedora at least."}, {'account_id': 2271, 'date': '2013-08-07 02:02:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

@padraig -- you make a fair point. The next steps for this code are log rotation, and perhaps interactive consoles in icehouse. We could use conserver for the logging, but then the get_console_output() call would need to understand how conserver was configured to fetch the data requested. I do worry that people fiddling with conserver would break that API call without realizing.

I also don't see any unix domain socket support in conserver (the docs aren't great though, am I missing something?) so I'm not 100% sure how we'd actually hook conserver up to livbirt. Libvirt itself has this page (http://wiki.libvirt.org/page/LibvirtConsoleManagement) as documentation, but it doesn't sound great to me.

Thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 1812, 'date': '2013-08-07 02:24:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

For what it's worth I see the changelog for the Fedora 8.1.18-1 here says:

'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2013-09-17 12:28:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18: (6 inline comments)

'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2013-09-17 16:12:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 18:

Looking at the permission issue, I think we would be better served by using a rootwrap helper program . 

Create a program 'nova-console-helper' that is give a UNIX console path as an arg.

Nova would call socketpair() using AF_UNIX and spawn the nova-console-helper program via rootwrap, setting the one of the just opened sockets as stdin/stdout of the program.

The nova-console-helper is now running as root and can connect to the guest console's UNIX socket. It can now pass the socket FD back to the main nova process using SCM_RIGHTS over the stdout FD (which is one of the earlier socketpair)

The main nova process can receive the FD via SCM_RIGHTS by reading from the child's stderr in a suitable manner.

This avoids any need to configure any permissions such that both Nova and QEMU can read/write to the same console socket. The socket will always be owned by qemu, and rootwrap + FD passing gives Nova access when it needs."}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2013-09-17 19:41:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I really think we need something better than "chmod 777" before putting this into the tree.'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2013-09-18 09:18:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 2271, 'date': '2013-09-20 20:19:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18: Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Add support for unix domain sockets as console logs

This is the first step in offering interactive consoles via libvirt.

DocImpact: For this change to work for you, you'll need to either
disable apparmor or alter the libvirt templates to allow access to
/tmp. You also need to change the value of the console_log_type flag
to "domain".

Sneaks up on bug 832507, progresses blueprint fix-libvirt-console-logging.

Change-Id: I6d65acf74e6d2734c16ccea243b3110a97e7f792

commit_message:
Limit resources per stack in nested stacks

In an earlier patch, the root stack creation was limited by the
max_resources_per_stack config setting. Now we need to apply the same
limit for nested stacks.

Change-Id: I2f871a5d5f4c51dd9cd7c93e94f8b0c8d87fa069
Partial-Bug: #1215100

subject: Provide config option to limit resources per stack

commit_message:
Provide config option to limit resources per stack

This provides an upper bounds on the number of resources a root level
stack can contain. The limitation is only applied to the engine creation
point so that existing stacks that are over the limit in the database
will not cause problems. Nested stacks will be addressed in a follow-up
patch.

Partial-Bug: #1215100
Change-Id: I1adcb22cf9bd5750b4ae3f219dd3264d1d02c1fc

(1 inline comment)

Is it the intention of the test changes to verify the moved code paths?

When I set a break point in the code under the unit tests I was not able to step through it, and the code coverage report for "./.unittests proxy/test_server.py" does not seem to include the lines changed in utils.py.

Otherwise, the changes seem fine. :)'}, {'account_id': 995, 'date': '2013-09-18 21:43:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

isn;t that code tested by some container server tests? its just pulling out some logic there and putting it in utils.  why would i need separate tests for it?'}, {'account_id': 995, 'date': '2013-09-18 21:47:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

hm- maybe not...'}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-09-18 21:58:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

So I believe the problem with having other modules create coverage for a given module means that if work is done on that other module, and the unit tests are changed, we can loose coverage on the module in question, allowing bugs to creep in later.

And how would a developer check that case? One would have to have a mechanism which ensures that code coverage does not drop for any module for a given commit.

So checking to see that a given modules unit tests create coverage for that module seems to be the easiest solution to maintain.'}, {'account_id': 995, 'date': '2013-09-20 15:51:35.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-09-20 16:07:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-05 21:25:01.000000000', 'message': 'Fix snapshot in VMWwareVCDriver

Fixes: bug #1184807

The snapshot operation was failing because it calls
VirtualDiskManager.CopyVirtualDisk with a destination disk spec, which is not
supported when called through VC. The fix is to not supply a spec when calling
through VC, in which case the disk is consolidated and copied without type
transformation.

While the fix is to use spec-less CopyVirtualDisk in VC, doing so in ESX too
will result in unintended transformation (because it ESX will default to
busLogic/preallocated), so the use of the spec was retained in ESX-mode instead.

Another issue found and fixed is that the name of the snapshot image is
incorrectly set when uploading to glance.

verified that:
- "nova image-create" now works
- the following tempest tests are now unbroken against the VC and ESX nodes:
     tempest.api.compute.images.
        test_images_oneserver.ImagesOneServerTest{JSON,XML}.
           test_create_delete_image
           test_create_second_image_when_first_image_is_being_saved
           test_delete_image_of_another_tenant
        test_list_image_filters
     tempest.api.compute.test_authorization.AuthorizationTestJSON \xa0\xa0\xa0\xa0
     tempest.api.compute.test_authorization.AuthorizationTestXML

Change-Id: I7ec49859fb2842cc02cdc87a6434aa58612a2964

commit_message:
Fix snapshot failure with VMwareVCDriver

The snapshot operation was failing because it calls
VirtualDiskManager.CopyVirtualDisk with a destination disk spec, which
is not supported when called through VC. The fix is to not supply a spec
when calling through VC, in which case the disk is consolidated and
copied without type transformation.

While the fix is to use spec-less CopyVirtualDisk in VC, doing so in ESX
too will result in unintended transformation (because it ESX will
default to busLogic/preallocated), so the use of the spec was retained
in ESX-mode instead.

Another issue found and fixed is that the name of the snapshot image is
incorrectly set when uploading to glance.

The following tempest tests are now unbroken against the VC and ESX
nodes:
  tempest.api.compute.images.
     test_images_oneserver.ImagesOneServerTest{JSON,XML}.
        test_create_delete_image
        test_create_second_image_when_first_image_is_being_saved
        test_delete_image_of_another_tenant
     test_list_image_filters
  tempest.api.compute.test_authorization.AuthorizationTestJSON
  tempest.api.compute.test_authorization.AuthorizationTestXML

Fixes bug 1184807

Change-Id: I7ec49859fb2842cc02cdc87a6434aa58612a2964

commit_message:
Fix for os-availability-zone/detail returning 500

if there are no enabled_services, then zone_hosts is very likely
to be empty, which means zone_hosts['nova'] will fail. So let's
use get with a default of empty array to cover this case. Added
a fix/test for v3 API as well.

Fixes LP# 1226791

Change-Id: I602c96242291fd9a4bdf67af6445aa935ec7f7e3

commit_message:
Fix unsuitable assertTrue

assertTrue accepts a parameter msg which will be printed when
assertion fails, usually msg is a str. This patch fixes unsuitable
usage of assertTrue which set msg to bool type True.

Change-Id: I731f8ea553c935eba0e112ffded16f41a5ea86c0
Fixes-Bug: #1226374

wsme have a couple of bugs:
 https://bugs.launchpad.net/wsme/+bug/1227004

commit_message:
xenapi: ensure finish_migration cleans on errors

This change makes finish_migration share code with spawn.

This fixes some inconsistencies, such as applying the security
group filters during finish_migration.

Fixes bug 1073303
Fixes bug 1073306

Change-Id: Ib4f2a96618692c141708535f9463c856f3395922

'}, {'created': '2013-08-06 17:25:34.000000000', 'message': 'xenapi: regroup spawn steps for better progress

Currently the operations are not very logically grouped. Now we can see
all the individual actions more clearly, we can re-arrange the
operations so each step make more sense, and should be better at
reporting progress.

Rather than checking very late that there is no duplicate VM and enough
memory, I have moved these checks before the expensive operation of
downloading the disk.

After this change there are 10 clear steps during spawn:
* initial step so progress is not zero during download disks
* download and create disks step
* download and create kernel and ramdisk step
* create the VM record, now the disks have been downloaded
* setup the disks; resizingi up disk, and attaching, adding rescue disk
* injecting instance data, currently this means writing to xenstore
* setting up the networking, including the initial firewall setup
* starting the VM and waiting for it to boot
* configuring the VM using the agent (takes a long time on windows)
* applying the final firewall filters, now the VM is running

With this in place, it will be easy to decide which steps are required
and which are not required when reusing the spawn code to implement
finish_migration in a later change.

Change-Id: I0e33dd7d298390630f632e116c8866a64e769102

commit_message:
xenapi: regroup spawn steps for better progress

Currently the operations are not very logically grouped. Now we can see
all the individual actions more clearly, we can re-arrange the
operations so each step make more sense, and should be better at
reporting progress.

Rather than checking very late that there is no duplicate VM and enough
memory, I have moved these checks before the expensive operation of
downloading the disk.

After this change there are 10 clear steps during spawn:
* initial step so progress is not zero during download disks
* download and create disks step
* download and create kernel and ramdisk step
* create the VM record, now the disks have been downloaded
* setup the disks; resizingi up disk, and attaching, adding rescue disk
* injecting instance data, currently this means writing to xenstore
* setting up the networking, including the initial firewall setup
* starting the VM and waiting for it to boot
* configuring the VM using the agent (takes a long time on windows)
* applying the final firewall filters, now the VM is running

With this in place, it will be easy to decide which steps are required
and which are not required when reusing the spawn code to implement
finish_migration in a later change.

Change-Id: I0e33dd7d298390630f632e116c8866a64e769102

commit_message:
xenapi: stop injecting the hostname during resize

The windows PV tools will set the hostname of a server to the value
given in the hostname xenstore key. If we inject that during resize, the
users will be unable to change their server hostname, and in addition it
will be reset to the original name.

Fixes bug 1207829
Change-Id: I49ba9d9f4f8b4a86488e427d99f69236bd959c78

xenapi: add tests for finish_migration and spawn

Before making finish_migration and spawn share more code, lock down the
current code with unit tests.

There are also some methods that are split up, to help with some of the
next refactoring steps.

commit_message:
replace hard coded url for vnc view

The URL for VNC view is hard coded to /project/instances/[instance_id]/vnc,
which will fail, if the dashboard is not placed in the root of the
web server.

Fixes bug 1228033

Change-Id: Ib0bb76f03b3adf6bd0d85230a292dec62298ecc4

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-17 00:07:26.000000000', 'message': "Ensure driver is initialized (WIP)

The manager calls the driver in many places
without ensuring that the driver has been
properly initialized.   When the driver fails
the do_setup, shouldn't call the driver's
set_initilialized() method.

Fixes bug #1225897

Change-Id: I77b947f2a9fbe1b38f321511dba10fcd2fe1fe90
"}, {'created': '2013-09-17 21:56:16.000000000', 'message': "Ensure driver is initialized

The manager calls the driver in many places
without ensuring that the driver has been
properly initialized.   When the driver fails
the do_setup, shouldn't call the driver's
set_initilialized() method.

commit_message:
Enforce driver is initialized

This updates the volume manager and the
backup manager to enforce that the driver
has been initialized.

The managers call the driver in many places
without ensuring that the driver has been
properly initialized.   When the driver fails
inside of do_setup(), the managers shouldn't
call the driver's set_initialized() method.
The managers now dump out the exception, and
exit the init_host, leaving the driver in
an uninitialized state.

Fixes bug #1225897

Change-Id: I77b947f2a9fbe1b38f321511dba10fcd2fe1fe90

I'm not sure I understand what the advantage of having a default provides is?"}, {'account_id': 7366, 'date': '2013-09-19 17:03:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Jessica,

The main advantage of having default provides is that you don't need to specify it when you create task instance. This is pretty much the same as inferring requirements from argument names, with the difference that method or function return values in not named in python, so names should be put somewhere else.

Also, decorators allow to specify 'provides' at task definition, so I thought that task.Task should allow that, too.

In case you missed it, there is small example that illustrates default_provides: http://paste.openstack.org/show/47209/ . It is  updated version of https://github.com/stackforge/taskflow/blob/master/taskflow/examples/complex_graph.py"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-20 17:36:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: No score

commit_message:
Allow to specify default provides at task definition

It is now possible to specify what task provides when task class
(deriving from taskflow.task.Task) is defined, using 'default_provides'
class attribute or property. This specification may still be overridden
when task instance is created via 'provides' constructor parameter.

Change-Id: If300c3a35807422d06c0196e84891faebde83c02

commit_message:
Distributed (Event-Driven) Engine

Distributed Engine is an engine that can doesn't care about patterns,
only task relations, and runs flows based on those relations.
Because of this, distributed translator is larger than other translators
(as it must account for all possible flows and their relations).

Change-Id: Id121ebbb59f6a52cc6b1ae6f7e7c6e87f2290035

commit_message:
Novaclient shell list command should support a minimal server list

The Nova API supports both a basic (id and name) and detailed server
list, and this is supported in the client by the "detailed=True"
argument to servers.list().  However the shell do_list() method always
leaves this to its default value.  For administrators on a large
system, or where the tenants has a lot of instances a detailed list
can be painfully slow.

This change adds support for a --minimal option to list.

Fixes bug: 1228137

Change-Id: I3126ee6b372606a98f0d7a4e344556f8c05ae224

[{'created': '2013-09-16 05:18:30.000000000', 'message': 'Add a flow flattening util

Instead of recursively executing subflows which causes
dead locks when they parent and subflows share the same
executor we can instead flatten the parent and subflows
into a single graph, composed with only tasks and run
this instead, which will not have the issue of subflows
dead locking, since after flattening there is no concept
of a subflow.

Change-Id: I79b9b194cd81e36ce75ba34a673e3e9d3e96c4cd

commit_message:
Add a flow flattening util

Instead of recursively executing subflows which causes
dead locks when they parent and subflows share the same
executor we can instead flatten the parent and subflows
into a single graph, composed with only tasks and run
this instead, which will not have the issue of subflows
dead locking, since after flattening there is no concept
of a subflow.

Fixes bug: 1225759

Change-Id: I79b9b194cd81e36ce75ba34a673e3e9d3e96c4cd

commit_message:
Hide the View Details for swift pseudo-folder

Pseudo-folder does not have any metadata information. The
View Details action should be just hidden for this type
of object.

Change-Id: Ic6c719444b41b23a4c86ba9433daed2041d5bd24
Closes-Bug: #1227953

replace nova flavor_list call with trove call

instead.

commit_message:
Provide new API endpoint for alarm state

This patch add a new endpoint to the alarm API to change only the state
of an alarm. And modifies the evaluator base to use this new endpoint.

Implements blueprint alarming-logical-combination

Change-Id: I8bff74f0686ba17103ee63bcbdb0830c8273596f

commit_message:
gettextutils: port to Python 3

- Everything's unicode in Python 3, so ugettext() has been removed.
  Let's use gettext() instead.
- Don't rely on builtins, and fix various unicode compatibility.
- Simplify check if a dict as params works; the test MIGHT work most
  of the time, but there is _no_ guarantee that str(somedict) returns
  always the result; in Python 3, sometimes the keys are iterated in a
  different order, returning a different result. Since anyway the dict
  is converted using str(), there's no really point for this test.
  We just a dict with one item to avoid the item order issue.

Change-Id: I1fc8991b3387dd56627b9f7f7833d2971cab059f

However, I don't understand why you've removed the checks for internal_attrs. It seems unrelated to this change, and it's not explained in the commit message (and I also think that was a good check to have).

Also, since this is ostensibly fixing a bug, I'd like to see a unit test added for the new/correct behavior (lest the bug creep back in later on).

Cheers!"}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2013-09-16 17:48:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Right, so before as we would update every attribute from the resource (even the ones that haven't changed) I added that test to remove the internal attributes so the update won't fail. (create/updated_at expects a datetime object for e.g).

But now we will just update the fields that actually changed so that remove is not needed anymore. Also, removing that fields will give me some KeyError when interaction between the fields from that resource, since they won't be part of the patch anymore.

I can reintroduce that check but in a different way: When interacting between the fields I can just check for those attributes and and "continue" avoiding then to be updated. I'm going to submit a new patchset doing this so u can take a look.'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2013-09-16 19:11:34.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-16 19:16:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

commit_message:
Update only the changed fields

When updating a resource do not update fields that haven't changed, it's
causing obj_what_changed() method from objects to return untouched fields.

Change-Id: I1ecebbddb0fe73b54f7044ebcc2f0f1d9fc66c87

Implement the combination evaluator

The implementation of the combination evaluator.
'and' and 'or' operations are allowed.

Implements blueprint alarming-logical-combination

Change-Id: Ie6b7dedc8aa5debb250c83e1c6db05c0d66eea1b

commit_message:
xenapi: ensure pool based migrate is live

The current code is missing a flag to pool_migrate that should be
included to ensure the migrate is live. This change adds that flag to
both uses of VM.pool_migrate, namely the live-migrate call and the
host_maintenance call.

Fixes bug 1201795
Change-Id: I265baaba5e9bd9132bd5e1c6f9fb18cefab02cfb

commit_message:
Make os-apply-config read on-disk config files

os-collect-config was changed recently to save the list of collected
files on disk, and not just in OS_CONFIG_FILES. This will allow
os-apply-config to be run outside of os-collect-config and still have
access to the latest copies of collected metadata.

Change-Id: I520f1332e5789e24562300f38af02b37a062ab48

commit_message:
Add alarm combination API

This change add a new type of alarm in the API for creating
alarm that combine the state of other alarms.

Implements blueprint alarming-logical-combination

Change-Id: I3203ae6143f5e21b5160a9a04692e7a4c8e550b8

commit_message:
Make run_tests.sh identify requirements correctly

We need to check requirements.txt and test-requirements.txt
in parallel to ensure both are satisfied and we don't upgrade
a package beyond requirements.txt's limits when installing
dependencies for test-requirements.txt

Fixes bug: 1227019

Change-Id: I606f8a1d3eed5c270d5b3c154994d5c3a17b98c8

commit_message:
Adds tests covering Swift's container quotas middleware

The execution of the tests is conditional to a setting declared
in the config file (container_quotas_available by default to True).

There are 3 tests:
 + User uploads an object smaller than the quota successfully
 + User fails to upload an object larger than the bytes quota
 + User fails to upload many objects that exceeds the count limit

Closes-Bug: 1225891
Change-Id: Id93f6c3628624f115a3c7a91de8a8e7894003f3f

commit_message:
Adds EDP support in the UI for job execution

First pass at job execution in the UI.  Job binaries
tab has been added, still needs work to handle internal
and external sources as well as overall refinement of controls.
Now includes job_binaries as a form rather than a workflow and
forces a unique name for binary-internal uploads.

Implements: blueprint edp-savanna-dashboard-ui

Change-Id: Id32f7c5d5458918bd832070c53271c042d886f86

commit_message:
Fix timeutils.set_override_time not defaulting to current wall time

This patch modifies timeutils.set_override_time so that it does not
default to setting the override to the current time when the function
*definition* is executed, but rather defaults to using the current
time at the moment the function is *called*.

The thinking is that this behavior is more along the lines of what
the developer would expect when using this function. The new behavior
is called out explicitly in the docstring.

Change-Id: I5a2d449c76a392c902d7a89617d63d7f1e896276

commit_message:
Add a test for creation of volumes' snapshots.

A new test called 'test_snapshot_create_get_delete' is added.
Also adds setUpClass and tearDownClass methods to create a
shareable volume origin.
Finally updates the existing 'test_volume_from_snapshot' which
now uses the create_* and clear_* wrappers from base class and
the shareable volume origin from setUpClass method.

Change-Id: I3fb8edabaf4649736a43d6de5a9c4518d3caac62
Implements: blueprint add-snapshot-tests
(cherry picked from commit 7333293fb549cb88a26246ddcd2f0c6bc812ce74)

commit_message:
Remove wait_for_image_resp_code

The nova api first creates an entry in glance,
before responding to snapshot creation request, so the entry
expected to be visible without any additional wait.

This change also introduces an OK code checker on the rest_client side,
it's extended usage can make unnecessary to assert the ok codes in the
test codes.

So the wait_for_image_status will implicitly validate the status code.

Change-Id: I9fdc1cc68501220e6688e2d7a745195b56d60cb9

commit_message:
Notify with string representation of alarm reason

Fixes bug 1227668

Ensure string representation of alarm reason is passed to the
alarm notifier over RPC (as opposed to a gettextutils.Message
instance).

Change-Id: I6a840789f83068ee5721cb139b06cf0071240152

commit_message:
Skip test tokens

This patchset skips test_token test due to the change of 401 response
for an invalid token to a 404 response.  Keystone bug 1221889.

Once the change to keystone has been accepted, a subsequent patchset
will be proposed to tempest to renable the check and accept the new
404 HTTP status for the get_token call on invalid tokens.

related-bug: 1221889
Change-Id: I3c5691f5085e10e28b0f57505133ae3478167396

commit_message:
Added unique constarint to quota_classes table.

Added unique constraint 'uniq_quota_classes0class_name0resource0deleted'
(columns - 'class_name', 'resource', 'deleted') to QuotaClass model.
Added new exception `QuotasClassExists`. Updated function quota_class_create()
Tests updated respectively.

part of blueprint db-unique-keys

commit_message:
This adds a transport layer request spec class.  The idea here is to be
declarative i.e. specify *what* is desired. It's up to the respective
transport to turn a request spec into an appropriate request.

The request spec class also performs some basic request validation.
My assumption is that the Marconi API is stable and known for a given
version. I am hence capturing the API info for version 1 in the code and
not fetching the home document.

Nevertheless I have introduced a separate api_info() function that
allows us to source the API info via the home document at a later point.

Change-Id: I8e30a2e09c6672f291149e02dbe3a78795b41931

Update glance::notify::rabbitmq options

class to keep consistent with glance-api.conf. And fix description

commit_message:
Add ratelimiting options to nova::api

nova master now has proper support for ratelimitng via the api-paste.ini
This commit adds a configuration option based on
https://github.com/openstack/nova/commit/08d6932963c9cbbd605833933bf5ea0f66127dc4

Change-Id: Ic29d4aa15fdf8b4613a1c3a641c60e6d8377f418

commit_message:
Add ratelimiting parameters to cinder::api

Cinder master now has proper support for ratelimitng via
the api-paste.ini.

This commit adds a configuration option based on
https://github.com/openstack/cinder/commit/2acb6f329bb404e224e525b946c0aa6cdc74040c

Change-Id: I2bdbd5d917baaeaa151471a8b20b2d7939fcf82a

commit_message:
Creates an empty init script override file if necessary

Without this patch, puppet runs were failing with the following error:

(/Stage[main]/Cinder::Volume::Rbd/File_line[set initscript env]) Could not
evaluate: No such file or directory - /etc/init/cinder-volume.override

Change-Id: Ibf42b4b09441c8a044f50af62246be31fe584e1b

'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2013-07-22 10:29:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

HEy Marcos,

Thanks for the patch, I've a general thought about files under tools/

I wonder we should keep those files or just removing them! Are we actually using them? I don't see them being referenced anywhere.

I tried running tox and setup.py after removing them and everything worked just fine.

Thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 7550, 'date': '2013-07-22 10:53:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

hi, thanks for reviewing! The patch adds the ability to run marconi in a virtual environment, just as it happens with horizon.
I think tox and virtualenv have its own way of building the venv to run the tests in, that is why tox did not broke in spite of having cleared the folder.'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2013-07-24 07:06:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Hey,

Yeah, my concern about tox was that there was a time it used to use scrips under tools/ - because we configured it that way - and that's one of the reasons why those scripts exist.

TBH, I don't think we need those scripts, at least I never use them. If folks think they are useful then I'm fine with them. 

Wouldn't it be better to document the steps to get it running?

It can be done in 3 steps:

1) Create env
2) pip install marconi (from git)
3) execute marconi-server

Thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 7550, 'date': '2013-07-24 08:35:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

hi Flavio,

I do really think the scripts are going to be useful down the road. Creating/updating venv and running marconi in it with one line is convenient. Anyway, if the files are no longer needed, because of the way now tox executes, I think the tools folder should be removed or emptied altogether.'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2013-07-24 13:47:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hey Marcos,

Thanks a lot for your thoughts.

Just want to add that my previous thoughts are based on the fact that scripts under tools/ are meant to be used by developers and not for prod environments. 

That being said, I agree with removing the whole folder :)

Lets see what Kurt and other folks think and decide based on that.

Thanks a lot! :)'}, {'account_id': 6427, 'date': '2013-07-30 03:09:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

So, I don't mind having these scripts, but I agree that the tools folder needs to be removed since it is just cruft from the old way of doing things. If we do that, however, we need to find a new home for:

1. system-test-requires (move up one level and rename to system-test-requirements.txt ?)
2. production scripts, such as those contained in this patch (move to marconi/cmd and make entry points, or create a new folder?)

P.S. - Don't forget to update the commit message to follow the standard OpenStack format. :D"}, {'account_id': 7550, 'date': '2013-07-30 07:53:52.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-07-30 07:55:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2013-07-31 18:24:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@kurt,

1) Yup, moving system-test-requires to the top level sounds good to me

2) What kind of production scripts do you have in mind? Overall, having them under marconi/cmd makes sense. I want to make sure we're talking about the same thing here.

Cheers,
FF"}, {'account_id': 6427, 'date': '2013-08-14 22:12:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Thanks for your patience; I will try to get folks to review this patch in the next few days...'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2013-09-12 06:50:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Hey,

Thanks a lot for the patch.

TBH, I don't see the value of having these commands within Marconi. Let me explain why:

1) Creating an environment for Marconi requires 3 commands: Venv, pip, setup.py

2) Commands under cmd/ will be available *just* after running setup.py, which requires installing Marconi itself.

3) There are plenty of tools for creating environments easily and as said before, installing Marconi is very simple.

4) It'll be weird to have 'provision' commands along with Marconi services.

Hope the above make sense."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-09-20 06:03:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Abandoned

commit_message:
Fix Alembic alter_column name argument deprecated

The name argument to alter_column has been deprecated and is
now new_column_name. This patch changes name to new_column_name.

Fixes bug: 1224737

Change-Id: I1d74916b1aa984194ce35b24801bcf12b3102c44

"}, {'account_id': 2592, 'date': '2013-09-11 20:26:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: Do not merge

DHCP ports are created with specific device_ids and owners.  The real question is why are we ending up with ports that have owners, but not device_ids.  I'd rather see us fix the problem than workaround the bug."}, {'account_id': 6522, 'date': '2013-09-11 20:33:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

This doesn't appear to be a requirement, and due to a previous BP 
Change-Id: I228870669825405277de0505a3f2ece074918524

This behaviour is mostly intentional. The actual problem here is when first setting up a network, you can't create the dhcp port with-out ending with an auxiliary port that may never be used.

Please advise, this behaviour should not remain as is."}, {'account_id': 6522, 'date': '2013-09-12 01:51:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Ok, so from a usability standpoint the current implementation seems to make sense to me. I am not opposed to ports requiring a device-id/device-owner on create, but this doesn't seem to be assumed anywhere and also would appear tp create bigger work-flow disruption to current users (??). Second, from horizon which is probably the UI of least resistance for most users. After having created a network, if you try to create a port. You end with two ports created, unless you have the domain knowledge to set the device id to the right value."}, {'account_id': 2592, 'date': '2013-09-12 23:39:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

Horizon shouldn't be creating two ports.  The DHCP port should be created by the agent which means that the device_owner and device_id should be known at the time the DHCP agent creates the port.  Having a port with a device_owner and not a device_id should be rare."}, {'account_id': 6522, 'date': '2013-09-12 23:56:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

To be perfectly clear, Horizon doesn't create 2 ports.

But with any initial network setup, unless you create create a port with the dhcp device id you end up with two created ports. This can be superfluous action.Based on the blueprint mentioned, this is intended and unless the direction from here is to always require a device-id and device-owner for port creation. I would argue this change is a reasonable and desirable assumption to make."}, {'account_id': 7937, 'date': '2013-09-13 01:26:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

I see two problems here.

1. Network initialization is deferred until a port is created, per Change-Id: I228870669825405277de0505a3f2ece074918524

2. A call to create/update a subnet returns before the async call to create the dhcp port (if needed) is complete.

As for #1, if deferring the initialization of the network were an option the user must pass along in the "create network" request, then you could require the user to submit a request to "finalize" the network.

If this were the case, you could create the dhcp port (if needed) when a subnet is created/updated with dhcp enabled. Or, do so when the user "finalizes" the network.

As for #2, I don't think that call should return until the dhcp port is created, because you create a race condition when scripting a network, if you're creating ports immediately after creating a subnet.

With the proposed changes, the port being created could be the port consumed for dhcp. I don't think the user should be forced to create the port with a device id/owner to avoid this. And if #1 was corrected and the create/update subnet call did not return until the dhcp port was created, then this would not be an issue.

I admit, I have not studied the Neutron code, so I could be missing something. But this is what I'm seeing from a user's prospective.'}, {'account_id': 6522, 'date': '2013-09-13 01:59:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

Addressing #2, Because of the distributed nature of possible neutron infrastructure, waiting for port creation is not wise. Nor am I sure of all possible scenarios where possible edge cases in the different states of neutron device creation would expose possible race conditions. Also if you are aware of race conditions (with/without this change) that you have exposed, I would strongly suggest to focus on that.'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-09-20 06:03:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-09-20 06:03:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Abandoned

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}]

commit_message:
Port with DHCP Device required

DHCP Agent will continue to create dhcp port
when a port without dhcp device exists.
This causes unintended conflicts, reuse
existing port that is not attached to device.

Fixes: bug #1219795
Depends on Change-Id: Ib2a934e8d9f792e9a7aff7d3554e5d3d1ba0b962

Change-Id: I6d3c991046221e50c9fe4d9a11c92f5a553c7ba4

commit_message:
Monkey patch select in environment

Explicitly say what needs to be monkey patched in
environment/__init__.py. By doing this we are making the code easier to
read and select needs to be monkey patched in order for notifications to
work with keystone/openstack/common/rpc/impl_qpid.py. Without monkey
patching select, keystone will hang on sending a notification since
qpid_messaging won't operate properly when establishing a connection
with the qpid broker.

Change-Id: I4cbdf29924473a76ce459d969e5e7077aac5beb8
Closes-bug: #1224565

commit_message:
Ensure v2 tokens are correctly invalidated when using BelongsTo

Due to the optional paramater of the tenant on several v2 token
validation methods, we need to ensure that calling token validation
with different permutations of parameters does not lead to an incorrect
cache value being returned.  This is done by lifting the 'BelongsTo'
checks out of the token backend and into the Manager, in a layer above
where the token caching takes place.

Fixes bug 1226225

Change-Id: Ifa3162923ad41aac6a9e5d5b4996bc43dc9b11fb

commit_message:
Cleanup and consolidation of the roles.

The roles were getting extremely fine-grained, to the point where it seemed
unlikely to map to real deployments. Several of these were redundant,
unreferenced or referred to recipes that did not exist so they were removed.

os-block-storage-api.rb: consolidated
os-block-storage-scheduler.rb: consolidated
os-block-storage-worker.rb: invalid
os-compute-api-ec2.rb: consolidated
os-compute-api-metadata.rb: consolidated
os-compute-api-os-compute.rb: consolidated
os-identity-api-admin.rb: unused
os-identity-api.rb: consolidated
os-image-api.rb: consolidated
os-image-registry.rb: consolidated
os-infra-caching.rb: unused
os-object-storage.rb: invalid

The other changes were to accomodate these updates.

commit_message:
Rewrite README.rst

Most of the content in the README is unmaintained and out of date, and
can be replaced by references to documentation that *is* more properly
maintained.

This patch replaces most of the contents of the README with
low maintenance links.

Fixes-Bug: 1227734
Change-Id: I4d63d971f94329197bd7001682d0d655901457f0

I checked out the docs at http://modwsgi.readthedocs.org/en/latest/configuration-directives/WSGIDaemonProcess.html and they do say you can pass user=whoever to WSGIDaemonProcess to do this.'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2013-09-19 08:57:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

"Also be aware that mod_wsgi will not allow you to run a daemon process group as the root user due to the security risk of running a web application as root" -- but running *apache* as root so it can setuid all over the place is fine.  crazy.

Anyone heard from David Hadas - he does this apache stuff right?'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2013-09-19 16:04:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

I am assuming that the USER variab le is already present in the deployment mechanisms.'}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2013-09-19 23:21:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@ayoung The USER variable was added to the sed template in devstack. See: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/46856/

@clay: Apache by default downgrades the worker threads into to a user context. This user is typically set in httpd.conf (or apache2.conf). By default mod_wsgi workers will be spun up as that user, this just allows us some finer control. See: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/46857/ for some more context.'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2013-09-20 03:01:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer); Approved

commit_message:
Add a user variable to templates

This is a common configuration option and allows devstack (and others)
to configure a mod_wsgi user to run the daemon process.

Change-Id: Idf134b3bc6b08e3c3a80dde8830d5a4f3da5a06c
Fixes: bug 1226346

commit_message:
Encode values as utf-8 before encrypting

Ensure strings are correctly encoded before encrypting

This is necessary because some encryption libraries don't handle
the unicode conversion appropriately.

Change-Id: Iebbf32e57ba21d955c1984ee32360379579366c8
Closes-Bug: #1207707

commit_message:
pci passthrough bug fix:hasattr dones not work for dict

hasattr only work in object model, scheduler does not use the
object model yet. so fall back to dict model.

Closes-Bug: #1226348

Change-Id: Ifab4165be67abfe2bbe9ac7280b8715cb7f04f1c
Signed-off-by: Yongli He <yongli.he@intel.com>

'}, {'account_id': 616, 'date': '2013-09-10 18:27:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Looking at how the existing metadata encryption works, I don't think this patch is heading in the right direction.

The existing metadata encryption consists of two parts. For v1, all encryption and decryption takes place in the registry client. For v2, there is a little adapter step in the domain logic for the database code that decrypts on the way out of the db and encrypts on the way in.

I think we need to keep that model, if just for the sake of avoiding spreading these details all across the codebase."}, {'account_id': 6549, 'date': '2013-09-11 03:20:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Hi markwash, let me answer you questions and explain what I did here.


1. Correct thare are two parts contain encryption and decryption handing for glance-registry v1 and v2 api separately, and v2 part is in the domain at https://github.com/openstack/glance/blob/master/glance/db/__init__.py#L99 and L128 and that's ok. This bug/patch just for v1 part only but v2, so I'm not breaking existing model.


2. Actually on glance-registry v1 server side we also need encryption and decryption handing since when in glance-api v1 controller, image object has 'location' and 'location_data' two fields (keep Forward-compatible, jbresnahan's multi-location patch did), so when we want to save image's locations back to db in glance-registry v1 controller we need combine them back to 'locations' field (https://github.com/openstack/glance/blob/master/glance/registry/api/v1/images.py#L55). So without my this fixes, the combination handling will be failed since the location url string is different even they are same actually, and location db record will be duplicated, and image locations field will be wrong also when glance load it back on next time.

Thanks."}, {'account_id': 6549, 'date': '2013-09-11 04:57:24.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 6549, 'date': '2013-09-11 04:58:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

commit_message:
Adding encryption support for image multiple locations

Adding necessary encryption and decryption code to registry API v1
server and client side, in order to take care image's all locations but
single location only.

docImpact
Implement bp: image-location-status
Fixes bug: 1218712

Change-Id: I999426469c196da1094cc46b5237bf1bc2006877
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Add reserved in fixed-ip show API

fixed-ip has show,reserve,unreserve API,
but the show API doesn't return reservation info,
this makes the user hard to know if IP is reserved
or not.

Change-Id: Id36b49639f9b4009cacaeb0d963a34b1d219e468

[{'created': '2013-09-19 20:32:38.000000000', 'message': 'Make all os-collect-config polling distro agnostic

Ubuntu does not support journalctl (which we currently use
in toci_test.sh to poll for os-collect-config to finish).

This patch wraps our os-collect-config polling commands so that distro
specific commands can be used to poll for the events.

NOTE: eventually it would be cool to be able to poll for specific
heat events, etc.

Change-Id: I15db5ab57f32c5f365a702a4a6d20e2debc427bd
'}]
commit_message:
Make all os-collect-config polling distro agnostic

Ubuntu does not support journalctl (which we currently use
in toci_test.sh to poll for os-collect-config to finish).

This patch wraps our os-collect-config polling commands so that distro
specific commands can be used to poll for the events.

NOTE: eventually it would be cool to be able to poll for specific
heat events, etc.

Change-Id: I15db5ab57f32c5f365a702a4a6d20e2debc427bd

Can we either clean out the extras that are being added or explain why they're needed?"}, {'account_id': 2417, 'date': '2013-09-18 15:27:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

The reason for the extra iSCSI code is that NetApp LUNs get virtual geometry defined when they're created, based on the initial size of the LUN. This geometry ultimately limits the minimum and maximum sizes that the LUN can be resized to. If a LUN is created very small initially, and then resized to very large, it will fail due to the geometry limitations, so extra code is needed to detect that case and handle it be creating a new LUN of the appropriate size and copying the data over (efficient copies can be used, fortunately).

Without all of the extra geometry and sub-lun clone code, resizes would be limited to be within a factor of 50x or so of the original size and would fail beyond that.

Only iSCSI is affected, not NFS. And the resize code is shared between the expand function and the create-volume-from-snapshot-of-different-size function."}, {'account_id': 2417, 'date': '2013-09-18 15:42:18.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 5494, 'date': '2013-09-18 15:42:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

commit_message:
NetApp fix create vol different size than snapshot

This fixes the issue of creating vol of different
size than snapshot and creating cloned vol of
different size than original.

This change adds a lot of additional LUN geometry
and sub-LUN cloning code which is neccesary to
support extreme resizes, since normal resize
operations are limitted to be within a certain factor
of the original LUN size.

Closes-Bug:#1098581

Change-Id: I8652bfaa67c12c790fa80650a051497f70279b9c

subject: add seek() to CompressingFileReader
messages:
[{'account_id': 1009, 'date': '2013-09-17 19:31:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Internal client's make_request() method retries failed requests.  If the body of the request is read from the body_file parameter.  If a request is retried and the body_file has a seek() method, body_file.seek(0) is called.

CompressingFileReader needs to have a seek() method so that the above will work when the body_file is such an object.

This problem was recently discovered during testing.  It results in a file uploaded that is only part of the intended upload.

(If a reviewer checks, internal client and the rest of this code is not used anywhere in the swift code base.  However, it's used by other, external projects.)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-17 20:13:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Works for me

(2 inline comments)

I think flush would be wasted effort:

http://docs.python.org/2/library/zlib.html#zlib.Compress.flush

There may be a way to "shutdown" the object that works better with PyPy but in CPython I'm sure the "right" thing to do is just let GC handle it.  I don't know enough about how PyPy wraps zlib to say what's the "right" way to delete an unfinished compressor object - but I don't know if that's super critical?  Alex obviously has @portante thinking about these issues, maybe he could guide us on some best practices we can point to?  Hit 'em up on twitter!

Don't quite know what your comment means?  Are you saying the other change is a dependency?  If yes, please make it as such.

Otherwise if it's not a dependency the relationship is likely irrelevant."}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2013-09-19 14:19:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: (2 inline comments)

Umm... I just noticed, what's up with raising imported exception classes from hpclient and paramiko?

So this is going to bight you really hard, because there's no way the manager/caller is ever going to be able to keep track of all the exceptions that you're throwing, let alone when you add the other 15 drivers that may choose to do similar things.

Manager doesn't have access to Paramiko's exeption class, nor the hpclient exception class.  This is why we have the cinder exception class, so we can actually import easily and have knowledge.

I'd really like to see us start moving to the model of using the Cinder exceptions and the inheritance there so we can get better at catching exceptions."}, {'account_id': 7198, 'date': '2013-09-19 14:26:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

John, good to know that that is part of the problem.  With that said I don't think 3PAR is the only driver doing this.  There will be some work required to get the drivers away from doing this.  :-)"}, {'account_id': 5997, 'date': '2013-09-19 17:29:33.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-19 17:59:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

commit_message:
Add logging to prior to raising exceptions

This patch fixes an issue where exceptions
happen in the 3PAR drivers and the exceptions
aren't being logged to the log file.

Fixes bug #1225235

Change-Id: I8ec26fe3bee65106e01e956472e06acf1d5b9f77

commit_message:
VMWare: Disabling linked clone doesn't cache images

This fixes an issue when use_linked_clone is false and the image is
already in the cache.  The problem was that the image would be
copied from glance into the instance directory even if it was already
in the cache.  This change checks if the file is in the cache, only
copies from glance if it is not, and copies the image from the cache
into the instance directory if use_linked_clone is false.

Fixes: bug #1207064
Change-Id: If3a84fda3a2a34f0a4aca3946d0a274f44059eab

commit_message:
Adding Y value unit into linechart popup

- Adding a simplified solution of fetching a meter unit.
- Adding unit into linechart popup, (Rickshaw doesn't support label
  of axis, we may add it in the future, depending on new wireframes).

Fixes bug 1226489

Change-Id: I01aa27578b30e6ad0d27956a3ddd76663f7549ce

commit_message:
Force textmode consoles

Physical hardware often has console interception hardware for OOB
monitoring/management. Prevent the kernel from switching to a graphical
console mode so the hardware can do its job.

Related-Bug: #1178112
Change-Id: If6d36461f3bd4cc3e32877b6810035b5c5ac69f3

commit_message:
Changes documentation hyperlinks to be relative

On the "System Architecture" page of the developer documentation there
are hyperlinks to sections of the API documentation. These hyperlinks
assumed that the documentation has been placed in the web root and
did not work for documentation in a subdirectory. The hyperlinks
were changed to be relative.

Fixes bug: #1206569

Change-Id: Id2bffbeaba1a41f7e9f76f7eb5a849d66703a7e7

commit_message:
Adding multi-node DevStack template for Ubuntu

Adding a template that deploys a multi-node OpenStack installation using
DevStack. This template has been tested on Ubuntu and may work as-is on
Debian too.

Note that the security group resources require to use Neutron and Havana
Heat.

Change-Id: Ibdf4fe7407913f75b2253b09639554c013d31c01

commit_message:
Remove _assert_compute_node_has_enough_memory from filter_scheduler.py

Now the function _assert_compute_node_has_enough_memory has no use
in filter_scheduler.py, just remove it to make code more clean.

Change-Id: Ie6f104368140b69a60e124ea96ef6bf7715fe34e

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-06 16:30:46.000000000', 'message': 'xenapi: tidy ups to some spawn related methods

There were server methods using during spawn that are only used
internally, but not named that way. They have been renamed in this
change.

There were also several methods that are currently called in a single
place, but had logic around the call that should have been inside that
method. This has been tided up, so it will be easier to re-use and/or
move those calls in future refactoring.

This is one of the building blocks towards sharing more code between
spawn and finish_migration.

Change-Id: I424daf8334ad9904572b9df511d8e6bc1ff6d21f

commit_message:
xenapi: tidy ups to some spawn related methods

There were server methods using during spawn that are only used
internally, but not named that way. They have been renamed in this
change.

There were also several methods that are currently called in a single
place, but had logic around the call that should have been inside that
method. This has been tided up, so it will be easier to re-use and/or
move those calls in future refactoring.

This is one of the building blocks towards sharing more code between
spawn and finish_migration.

Change-Id: I424daf8334ad9904572b9df511d8e6bc1ff6d21f

subject: xenapi: move kernel/ramdisk methods to vm_utils

commit_message:
xenapi: move kernel/ramdisk methods to vm_utils

A previous change has now removed the duplication between spawn and
finish_migration, into create_kernel_and_ramdisk. This change moves the
code into vm_utils, and covers the code with some unit tests.

This will makes is easier to share code between spawn and finish_resize
and gives a more logical public interface to vm_utils.

I have also simplified the call to destroy_kernel_ramdisk in spawn so
that can be shared more easily between spawn and finish_migration in a
later change.

Change-Id: I73523d93be0a7afa9fe814af280c582e47064d69

commit_message:
Convert TestCases to NoDBTestCase

NoDBTestCase is faster because it skips initializing a database for
tests which don't actually talk to the database. Its also nicer
because its more explicit about the dependancies of a given test.
This is a first pass at moving test cases over to the database
lacking version, but further work is required here.

Change-Id: Ia28de4ebea4f354cba06bcdc66bb01d4b332943a
Partial-Bug: 1227473

commit_message:
Change daemon Pidfile class to not use root_helper

Some users of the Pidfile class don't specify root_helper,
which then defaults to 'sudo', which will generate an error.
Remove root_helper altogether since we actually don't need
root priveleges to read /proc/$pid/cmdline.

Changed code to use open.readline() instead of a shell, and
tweaked tests accordingly.

Also cleaned-up the rootwrap filters that allow it as they
are not used anymore.

Fixes bug 1218142

Change-Id: I6691feb1c9f7bfa261a7ec464fd8f3f92168c302

commit_message:
Update error messeages in Launch Instance

If no image is selected when launching an instance, we will get
an error message "There are no image sources available; you must
first create an image before attempting to launch an instance."
In most cases this message is displayed when a user forget to
select an image. This commit changes the error message more generic
to avoid unnecessary confusion.

Closes-Bug: #1225755

It also changes the menu to display "No images available" if
no images are available rather than "Selct image" with no choice.

Change-Id: Ie5dd0760349c8b030baa2b2465776d0fa6c1767f

commit_message:
Do not apply security groups to logical ports

Security groups rules were applied to logical ports and this caused
Floating IP not to work correctly.
Correct some typo.

Change-Id: I174e60f8eb8a4d00b71fffc127e2d2d36836835d
Closes-Bug: #1221336

commit_message:
Fix handling of floating IP association info in Nicira plugin

Bug 1223902

This patch fixes the _update_fix_assoc routine in the Nicira plugin,
ensuring the association of a floating IP with a router is removed
when the floating IP is disassociated.
This patch also adds a unit test for validating behaviour when a floating
IP is associated to a port on a different router, which was an
uncovered use case. This new unit test required some refactoring in
test_l3_plugin.py.

Change-Id: Ibfd53a637f4d14a368b0aeff289c15f993df58dd

commit_message:
Bugfix for ConfigManagers: defauls overwriting

In the previos version the read_from_dict() method of the test ConfigManager
classes did not overwrite the already existing options by default, which
resulted in the incorrect TestEngine.bind() behavious. This patch fixes this
issue, adds comments to the ConfigManager class and also makes one small
styllistic improvement in TestConfigManager.

Change-Id: Ie5943e6837405719694659d93912b6153601f878
Closes-Bug: #1227864

Typo: certicates=>certificates in nova.conf

neutron_ca_certificates_file spelled certificates wrong.

As this is user facing, we should fix it.

Fixes bug 1227780

This should not work any better but for a very subtle reason it does. The change here is that instead of waiting for either a "not found" or an "child exited" or... a clean exit... we poll until the process table says there is no process. That's subtly different and works-around a problem with this whole file in general. The file assumes that if there is a process table entry for a process then there *is* a process. This isn't true 100% of the time. There can be "zombie" processes which will have table entries... and more importantly... there may be a lag between when the process signals it has exited and the process table has been updated. By waiting around for the "not found" error we are guaranteeing that anything that comes looking for the process will find there is none and the process table is in sync.'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2013-09-12 21:24:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I'm confused, don't we still need to wait() in order to clean up the zombies?"}, {'account_id': 7629, 'date': '2013-09-12 21:58:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Hi Dan,

See: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_process

So basically, this set of tests hits that "zombie" problem pretty frequently. The way I've written the loop in this patch, we keep polling the pid until we get specifically err.errno == errno.ESRCH which is only thrown as an exception when the process is not found in the process table.

That basically does the job of not only waiting on the process to exit... but also for it to be reaped.

in short: waiting is semantically correct but not enough.'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-09-14 17:38:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
MultiprocessWSGITest wait for workers to die bug

MultiprocessWSGITest.test_terminate_sigterm
fails because the wait for workers to die is unreliable.

Parent process can now wait on child or grand-child
processes to complete before moving on. This allows
for grand-child (aka worker) processes to take as much
time as they need to shutdown. NOTE: If the processes
still take too long, they will be killed by the test
framework throwing the "TIMEOUT" exception.

Reverts to using a ping signal to child process
to determine if the child process is live. Waits for
the signal call to fail, signaling process death.

closes bug #1218133

Change-Id: I08e17005508fe412f462773f9ab212cf0f10382f

commit_message:
Enable fake driver can live migration

Now two methods of virt/fake.py does not implemented
1) ensure_filtering_rules_for_instance
2) unfilter_instance

Also the method live_migration does not call
post_live_migration_at_destination, this will cause compute
driver has no chance to update task state for the VM in DB.

Fix bug 1223090

Change-Id: I2fe552faa5f73b47b97e8fefc5c4de04d6785f8c

commit_message:
Wrong arguments when calling safe_utils.getcallargs()

When calling safe_utils.getcallargs(), it will get all argnames from
definition of a function. As every function in Nova has a argument named
`context`, so argnames will always start with `context`.

In nova/exception.py#81, *args is a list of arguments which does not
start with
`context`, however, argnames starts with `context`, this will lead to a
mismatching when zip it into a dict.

Solution for this is that when calling getcallargs(), pass context as
one argument.

Change-Id: I4ce81e1862fb2d741f15747b04aa6bf1a2243364
Fixes: bug #1207153

commit_message:
Creates multiple worker processes for API server

This change to the WSGI code uses openstack.common.service to create
multiple worker processes to handle API load.  The main process will
start up a configurable (workers=??) number of child processes which
will all listen on the bind port.

Implement blueprint multi-workers-for-api-server

Change-Id: I1d9b183e1ad8d172584e83ae67524e505e0f425f

commit_message:
Refactor threshold evaluator

This change creates a base class for evaluator.

The alarm service load all evaluators.
A evaluator needs to implement abstract method of this base class.

The alarm service now check in alarm.type use the right extension to
evaluate the alarm.

The previous threshold evaluator code has been moved into the threshold
extension.

Related to blueprint alarming-logical-combination

Change-Id: If6057b7db1e894333e6e9f1edb41ab75bc2c4444

Manager._list should always return a list

Convert single-row result sets to dicts for consistent
handling of single-element lists.

'}, {'account_id': 8415, 'date': '2013-09-08 12:28:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

I have few questions for you (in terms of current review):
1. Is it necessary to allow security group management to user?
2. Should it be moved to mgmt-cli ?

My point is, that endpoint user should only create/backup/restore databases and users. Networking is prerogative of adminstrator.'}, {'account_id': 739, 'date': '2013-09-10 03:38:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Well, some people have real requirements saying their database cant run on the advertised port, such as 3306. So for this, id say it makes sense for a user to be able to administer it. BUT, this only makes sense if we can change the port for a instance. Given that, maybe it doesnt make sense to allow users to admin this. Id like to see reasons for/against why we want to allow users to admin their own rules.

Id say lets add this to the meeting agenda for this week.'}, {'account_id': 8214, 'date': '2013-09-10 06:33:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

I think there are a couple of things to consider:

- If the user can create regular computes and associate/dissociate security groups at will, altering their rules when needed, then why can't they do the same for database "computes"? It's important to note that even if Trove attempts to stop them, if they have access in Nova, they can do whatever they want.

- As Michael pointed out, if the user desires to run the service on a non-standard port (and the api schema supports such a parameter), how can we accommodate it?

- Take Cassandra, which can require ports 7000/7001, 7199, and 9160. If CONF.security_group_support/rules == True, should all four ports automatically be opened?

- If as a cloud provider, you rely on a DevOps model, there must be a self-service means of shutting off traffic to the database. The easiest way as a user to accomplish this would be to delete the security group rule (e.g. for 3306). However, if the user is not allowed to modify or add/drop rules, the admin is left on the hook.

- Administrators need the ability to add a SSH (22) security group rule in situations that require them to get on the VM to triage (first-boot or agent upgrade issues, etc.)

- Users shouldn't be able to open up non-related ports on a whim.

All things considered, I'm thinking this is the right approach: each service type has a set of ports that can be considered eligible, as defined by the cloud provider.

Example #1: Cloud provider 'A' offers MySQL on 3306.
Example #2: Cloud provider 'B' offers MySQL on 3399, with a reverse proxy open on 6646.
Example #3: Cloud provider 'C' offers MySQL on 3306, with a custom agent (installed in the disk-image) on 9909

How can all of these be accomodated?

CONF.<service_type>_ports_eligible = List(Integer)
CONF.<service_type>_ports_applied = True/False
CONF.<service_type>_ports_user_access = True/False

Example:

CONF.mysql_ports_eligible = [3306]
CONF.mysql_ports_applied = True
CONF.mysql_ports_user_access = False
CONF.cassandra_ports_applied = True
CONF.cassandra_ports_eligible = [7000, 7001, 7199, 9160]
CONF.cassandra_ports_user_access = False

If _ports_applied is True, then all ports that are eligible are automatically applied on instance creation. If _ports_applied is False, then none are automatically applied (i.e. a security group with no rules). If user_access is True, the user is free to add/drop/modify security group rules, as long as the port(s) are eligible. If user_access is False, then the administrator is the only one capable of modifying security group rules. (Corner Case: If an administrator adds a rule to an instance that includes a port that is not in the eligibility list, even if user_access is True, the user cannot drop it)'}, {'account_id': 8214, 'date': '2013-09-10 06:39:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Gerrit formatting is a bit wonky, please see https://gist.github.com/amcrn/14501657c5a5e9ee78dd for a pretty-printed version of what I stated above.'}, {'account_id': 694, 'date': '2013-09-17 18:08:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Change seems good. Let's talk about whether to allow non-admins to use this feature at the next meeting."}, {'account_id': 1925, 'date': '2013-09-18 06:26:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Hi Auston.  I think I am ok with what I saw in the gist.  However, that's not reflected in this patchset.  

I would even be open to considering putting the port info for a given instance as part of the instance record.  When determining which ports to open, that would be the place to look."}, {'account_id': 8214, 'date': '2013-09-19 19:49:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Security Group Rule's To/From/Protocol Ignored

A Security Group Rule can be created via the CLI like so:

$ trove-cli secgroup add_rule --secgroup_id 2263 --protocol tcp \
    --from_port 88 --to_port 88 --cidr 0.0.0.0/0

From the blueprint (bp/security-groups), it seems the intent was to
support multiple rules for a security group. However, the add_rule
method completely disregards the from_port, to_port, and protocol
values, instead opting for the defaults set in the CONF.

Changes:

- All add_rule arguments are now required (no defaults)
- Schema validation is now enabled for add_rule (prior to this
  changeset, the validation was never ran due to the 'create' action
  missing in the schema)
- to_port/from_port validation has been enhanced to detect invalid
  ranges, as well as support regex approved numeric strings.

Closes-Bug: #1199623
Change-Id: I7466046c4641c22e5be30467e68953e0e0582fa6

commit_message:
Alarm API update

This updates the alarm API to match the latest discussion:

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Ceilometer/blueprints/alarm-api

It allows creation of different kinds of alarm.
The current kind of alarm has been named 'threshold'.

It move the defaults values from the storage models to the API
with all tools provided by wsme to ensure mandatory field and default.

A behavior change, it is now mandatory to PUT a full alarm description
in a PUT call.
In the future a new endpoint can be added to allow to modify only one
field (example for state: /v2/alarms/<id>/state)

Implements blueprint alarming-logical-combination

Change-Id: Ib85636728d427cdb70ef530ff9ff20d2b75c5ed1

[{'created': '2013-09-19 15:19:31.000000000', 'message': 'Fix ovs-vsctl call in add_tunnel_port()

When a new GRE tunnel is created OVS agent calls ovs-vsctl
incorrectly. Command:

    sudo ovs-vsctl --timeout=2 --may-exist add-port br-tun gre-1

is produced instead of correct one:

   sudo ovs-vsctl --timeout=2 -- --may-exist add-port br-tun gre-1

Fixes bug 1227675

Change-Id: I010961658a37028e41621c4a529b5a14e7587c7f
'}]
commit_message:
Fix ovs-vsctl call in add_tunnel_port()

When a new GRE tunnel is created OVS agent calls ovs-vsctl
incorrectly. Command:

    sudo ovs-vsctl --timeout=2 --may-exist add-port br-tun gre-1

is produced instead of correct one:

   sudo ovs-vsctl --timeout=2 -- --may-exist add-port br-tun gre-1

Fixes bug 1227675

Change-Id: I010961658a37028e41621c4a529b5a14e7587c7f

commit_message:
Send notification for any updates to instance objects

Before objects, a notification would be sent for any change to an
instance and the notifications.send_update method would handle any
filtering that needed to be done prior to sending the event.

Currently, the instance objects code is pre-filtering the notification
by only checking if vm_state or task_state changed which is a
regression.

This patch removes the filter in the instance objects code so that
notifications are again sent for any changes to the instance and lets
the notifications.send_update method handle the event as it did before.

Closes-Bug: #1220186

Change-Id: Ib6ceedfe55b021be0fe7fa910e97d46c0cd8f0cd

commit_message:
Retry on deadlock in instance_metadata_delete

Add the retry_on_deadlock decorator to the instance_metadata_delete
function in the sqlalchemy db API.  A tempest test failure shows that it
would benefit from it.

Change-Id: I39547fbbbabc310b78493df0dc055bc320995770
Closes-bug: #1226076

commit_message:
Provide Neutron password in compute metadata

overcloud compute node makes requests to Neutron API
and requires quantum_admin_password option of nova.conf
to be set (it is defined in nova image element like
quantum_admin_password={{neutron.service-password}}).

Without this, booting of a user instance in overcloud
fails, because nova-compute service can't authorize
requests to Neutron API.

Change-Id: Ie726d0c3d54abc6c24a45fde3f5af03fd2cf9e37

commit_message:
Use openstack-images-v2.1-json-patch for update method

image.patch returns a JSON schema Draft 10 (application/openstack-images-v2.1-json-patch)
while the glaceclient update method specify a Content-Type header
application/openstack-images-v2.0-json-patch with correspond to a JSON schemea Draft 4.

Fixes bug 1206095
Change-Id: I8c5a96f0e117a81b5b527a96ef45758fc69b518d

commit_message:
perf: Partition messages collection by project

This patch moves the project name out of the individual message documents
by creating per-project message collections instead. This reduces
the size and complexity of message indexes, as well as increasing the
performance of queries. Furthermore, it will make it more likely that
collections and associated indexes for busy projects are retained in
RAM when memory pressure forces paging.

Change-Id: I3c6a4937cc5735866c108c5a3323a3ea03553773
Implements: blueprint partition-messages-collection

commit_message:
Neutron nicira plugin: set up connectivity with public network

When spinning devstack with the Neutron and the Nicira plugin, the public
bridge is not configured since the external network will be implemented
on the NVP gateway appliance.

This patch therefore configures an IP address for the devstack interface
on the NVP gateway's uplink network thus providing IP connectivity with
the Neutron external network configured by devstack.
The configured IP address is the external network's gateway, in
accordance with similar setting for OVS-based plugins.

This patch also ensures the IP address is configured when devstack
is shut down.

Bug #1227757

Change-Id: I971eb75548af23c2c77506d48eabd49f2ddb7348

"Would it be possible to provide a migration that soft-deletes orphaned stats?"

So this patch fixes the root cause, but doesn't go back and fix stats for compute nodes that were removed without this patch.  Unfortunately Orphaned stats can break things, compute_node.stats won't get populated if there are orphaned stats, so we should provide deployers a way to soft-delete orphaned stats.

I see two possible solutions: add a database 'migration' to fix things, that way it runs only once, or just add documentation in the commit message on how to fix this in the database directly.  I would prefer a migration as that will make things easier for the deployer.'}, {'account_id': 7664, 'date': '2013-09-18 19:53:57.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 10.'}, {'account_id': 7664, 'date': '2013-09-18 19:55:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-12 23:06:10.000000000', 'message': "Move iterator creation into loop

When retrieving compute node stats, only the first node's stats were being
retrieved. This was caused by an interator being created outside of the nested
loops.

To handle this, we need to construct a fresh iterator each time before the
inner loop is executed.

Change-Id: Ief0f7cf1a506e71898b5a45a0513d34167432d67
Closes-Bug: #1224712
"}, {'created': '2013-09-14 07:27:54.000000000', 'message': "Add more test cases showing cascaded stat deletes

The respective bug report claims that deleting either a compute node or
compute service does not cause cascaded soft deletes of the compute node stats.

As such, this commit provides two new test cases that illustrate that the
compute node stats are indeed soft deleted when the db_api's compute node
or service deletion routines are invoked. Additionally, the conductor calls the
same APIs as well, so we should be covered there in terms of what these new
test cases are proving.

Change-Id: Ief0f7cf1a506e71898b5a45a0513d34167432d67
Closes-Bug: #1224712
"}, {'created': '2013-09-14 09:12:05.000000000', 'message': "WIP: Prune node stats at compute node delete time

This is a work in progress.

This commit addresses the situation in which a compute node is deleted, but
its compute node stats still remain in the database as **not** deleted. This
causes ill side effects in compute_node_get_all when it's retrieving host stats
as it doesn't expect there to be compute node stats for which there is no
corresponding compute node (i.e., causing some node's stats to be empty).

As such, when a compute node is deleted, its stats should also be implicitly
deleted.

Change-Id: Ief0f7cf1a506e71898b5a45a0513d34167432d67
Closes-Bug: #1224712
"}, {'created': '2013-09-14 10:21:46.000000000', 'message': "WIP: Prune node stats at compute node delete time

"}, {'created': '2013-09-18 19:57:58.000000000', 'message': "Prune node stats at compute node delete time

This commit addresses the situation in which a compute node is deleted, but
its compute node stats still remain in the database as **not** deleted. This
causes ill side effects in compute_node_get_all when it's retrieving host stats
as it doesn't expect there to be compute node stats for which there is no
corresponding compute node (i.e., causing some nodes' stats to be empty).

As such, when a compute node is deleted, its stats should also be implicitly
deleted.

The new test case that's been created fails without the code changes, which
illustrates the problem that compute node stats are empty when they should
not be.

commit_message:
Prune node stats at compute node delete time

This commit addresses the situation in which a compute node is deleted, but
its compute node stats still remain in the database as **not** deleted. This
causes ill side effects in compute_node_get_all when it's retrieving host stats
as it doesn't expect there to be compute node stats for which there is no
corresponding compute node (i.e., causing some nodes' stats to be empty).

As such, when a compute node is deleted, its stats should also be implicitly
deleted.

The new test case that's been created fails without the code changes, which
illustrates the problem that compute node stats are empty when they should
not be.

Also included is a simple DB migration script that will update old stats that
were not marked soft-deleted as they should have been.

Change-Id: Ief0f7cf1a506e71898b5a45a0513d34167432d67
Closes-Bug: #1224712

commit_message:
Updates documentation for tox use

In order to create a virtualenv with tox, a postgresql package is needed
as a prerequisite. The dev-quickstart documentation has been updated to
reflect this.

In addition, the prerequisites for Fedora/RHEL were modified, because
mysql-devel is needed, not mysql-libs.

Fixes bug: #1227390

Change-Id: Ibfdb0a9a3d560fcc3fb7d95aaa1d765ed18215e2

commit_message:
Fixes undercloud and overcloud credentials

renames TOCI_UNDERCLOUD|OVERCLOUD_PASSWORD to UNDERCLOUD|OVERCLOUD_ADMIN_PASSWORD
because these variables are expected to be set in undercloudrc and overcloudrc files.

Change-Id: I9947662b38d94c41bcfdb32e7c481f95e92bc47a

commit_message:
Use built-in print() instead of print statement

In python 3 print statement is not supported, so we should use
only print() functions.

Fixes bug 1226943

Change-Id: I05f042dc247ac117f6c2823d1326a88059875b79

commit_message:
Sync gettextutils from oslo

Some Messages, such as those created from Invalid exceptions, use a
Message within a Message, and we were only translating the base Message
but not the Message substitution within.

Fixes bug: #1221808

Change-Id: Ic3119df23a090cfaa160c1461e955f0af55fe1cf

commit_message:
Dump basic network info  in the test_network_basic_ops

Add minimal debug debug capability for basic network informations,
These information, especially the nat rules in the router namespaces
 usually very helpful.

Change-Id: I8840cb5e388fc8b674b66f8de4e25754ccbe0863

commit_message:
Add warning and workaround for selinux

Building a Fedora image from an Ubuntu guest runs into DIB bug
1204824. This provides a workaround until the DIB bug is resolved.

Change-Id: I1a4171d6f833b8989e19229fbe63f7a10011a95b

"}, {'created': '2013-09-18 16:07:15.000000000', 'message': "Add mongo driver for marconi proxy storage

This adds a mongodb storage driver for managing a marconi proxy
catalogue.

Requests are now also round-robin'd properly, rather than set once
based on queue.

Unit tests were added that give significant coverage of current and
future proxy storage driver implementations. These mirror the
conventions established by tests/unit/queues/storage, and add a
configuration file 'etc/wsgi_proxy_mongodb.conf'. The 'marconi_proxy'
DB is used by default.

Four new test helpers are introduced, all context_managers
- entry
- entries
- partition
- partitions

BREAKING CHANGE: proxy.utils.node
* rewrote weighted_select to be more functional, storage-independent
* rewrote round_robin to be more functional, storage-independent
* rationale: so that storage drivers can use this as needed

BREAKING CHANGE: removed caching
BREAKING CHANGE: removed round robin index from storage
BREAKING CHANGE: proxy.utils.helpers
* removed cruft functions
* updated forward to require only host and request

BREAKING CHANGE: storage interface
* updated to reflect actual usage of storage controllers

This patchset also updates the app and all resources to use the new
storage controllers.

Change-Id: If628f5ac74a340f613b65b695d72a62de5453566
Implements: blueprint placement-service
